Definition 8.1. Suppose $P$ and $Q$ are connected posets. For $p\in P,q\in Q$, we say that $p$ is taxotopic to $q$, written $p\preceq_{P}^{Q}q$, if there is an adjunction $f^{*}:Q\rightleftarrows P:f_{*}$ such that $f^{*}(q)=p$ and $f_{*}(p)=q$. More generally, for a fixed non-empty poset $S$, we say that $k:S\to P$ is taxotopic to $h:S\to Q$, written $k{}_{S}\preceq_{P}^{Q}h$, if there are adjunctions $e^{*}\dashv e_{*}$ on $S$ and $f^{*}:Q\rightleftarrows P:f_{*}$ such that $f^{*}\circ h=k\circ e^{*}$ and $f_{*}\circ k=h\circ e_{*}$.
Definition 11.10. Let $S,P$ be any two posets. For $h,k\in\operatorname{Pos}(S,P_{\bot})$, we say that $k\preceq^{*}h$ if there are $e\in\operatorname{Adj}(S)$, $f\in\operatorname{Adj}(P)$ such that $(e,f^{ext})\models k\preceq h$ where $f^{ext}\in\operatorname{Adj}(P_{\bot})$ is the unique extension of $f$. The notation $\Lambda^{*}(S,P_{\bot})$ will denote the posetal reflection of the preorder $(\operatorname{Pos}(S,P_{\bot}),\preceq^{*})$.
Definition 7.2. Fix a nonempty $S$. We say that a poset $P$ is taxotopic (resp. $S$-taxotopic) to $Q$, written $P\preceq Q$ (resp. $P\preceq_{S}Q$), if there exists a weak adjunction (resp. weak $S$-adjunction) $h^{+}:P\rightleftarrows Q:h_{+}$ where the right adjoint goes from $P$ to $Q$. We say that $P$ and $Q$ are taxotopy equivalent (resp. $S$-taxotopy equivalent), written $P\approx Q$ (resp. $P\approx_{S}Q$), if $P\preceq Q$ and $Q\preceq P$ (resp. $P\preceq_{S}Q$ and $Q\preceq_{S}P$). We say that a poset is null-taxotopic if it is taxotopy equivalent to $\mathbf{1}$.
Definition 11.2. Given $\emptyset\neq P\in\operatorname{Pos}$, $\emptyset\neq Q\in\operatorname{Sub}_{w}(P)$ and a homogeneous total order $S$, the inclusion map $i:Q\rightarrowtail P$ is said to induce taxotopy retracts of $S$-chains if the following condition is satisfied. For each $h\in\operatorname{Pos}(S,P)$ form the pullback $S\xleftarrow{j}S\times_{P}Q\xrightarrow{k}Q$. If $S\times_{P}Q\neq\emptyset$, then there is a diagonal $\widetilde{h}:S\to Q$ such that $\widetilde{h}\circ j=k$. If a diagonal $\widetilde{h}$ exists, then it is referred to as a taxotopy retract of the map $h$ with respect to $Q$.
Definition 6.1. Let $\emptyset\neq S\in\operatorname{Pos}$. A map $h\in\operatorname{Pos}(Q,P)$ is said to be $S$-continuous if whenever $k\preceq k^{\prime}$ in $\Lambda(S,Q)$ then $h\circ k\preceq h\circ k^{\prime}$ in $\Lambda(S,P)$. If we denote the subcategory of $\operatorname{Pos}$ consisting of $S$-continuous maps as $\operatorname{Cont}_{S}$, then $\Lambda(S,-):\operatorname{Cont}_{S}\to\operatorname{Pos}$ is a functor.
Definition 10.1. Let $P$ be a nonempty poset. A collection $\mathcal{Q}$ of subsets of $P$ is said to be a cover if it satisfies the following properties. • $\emptyset\notin\mathcal{Q}\subseteq\operatorname{Sub}_{w}(P)$. • $\mathcal{Q}$ is closed under nonempty finite intersections and $\bigvee\mathcal{Q}=P$. • For each $Q^{\prime}\subseteq Q$ in $\mathcal{Q}$, the inclusion $Q^{\prime}\rightarrowtail Q$ is in $\mathcal{R}$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathscr{F}_{1},\mathscr{F}_{2}\colon\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{C}^{\prime}$ be computable functors. A computable morphism of functors (or computable natural transformation) from $\mathscr{F}_{1}$ to $\mathscr{F}_{2}$ is a morphism of functors $\tau\colon\mathscr{F}_{1}\to\mathscr{F}_{2}$ such that there exists a Turing functional that on input $S\in\mathbf{C}$ computes the morphism $\tau(S)\colon\mathscr{F}_{1}(S)\to\mathscr{F}_{2}(S)$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathbf{C}$ and $\mathbf{C}^{\prime}$ be categories of structures on $\omega$ (with respect to possibly different languages $\mathcal{L}$ and $\mathcal{L}^{\prime}$). A computable functor is a functor $\mathscr{F}\colon\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{C}^{\prime}$ for which there exist Turing functionals $\Phi$ and $\Psi$ such that (i) for every $S\in\mathbf{C}$, the function $\Phi^{S}$ computes (the atomic diagram of) the structure $\mathscr{F}(S)$; and (ii) for every morphism $g\colon S\to T$ in $\mathbf{C}$, we have $\Psi^{S\oplus g\oplus T}=\mathscr{F}(g)$ in $\mathbf{C}^{\prime}$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathbf{C}$ and $\mathbf{C}^{\prime}$ be categories of structures on $\omega$. A computable equivalence of categories from $\mathbf{C}$ to $\mathbf{C}^{\prime}$ is a pair of computable functors $\mathscr{F}\colon\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{C}^{\prime}$ and $\mathscr{G}\colon\mathbf{C}^{\prime}\to\mathbf{C}$ together with computable isomorphisms $\mathscr{G}\mathscr{F}\to 1_{\mathbf{C}}$ and $\mathscr{F}\mathscr{G}\to 1_{\mathbf{C}^{\prime}}$.
Definition 3.3.6. Let $A$ be an additive category. Following Definition 4.3.1 of [Bon10] we call the full subcategory of $\operatorname{\operatorname{Kar}}(A)$ consisting of the objects $Y$ of $\operatorname{\operatorname{Kar}}(A)$ such that $X\oplus Y$ belongs to $\operatorname{Obj}A$ for some $X\in\operatorname{Obj}A$ the small envelope of $A$.
Definition 3.2.1. A class of morphisms $S\subset\operatorname{\operatorname{Mor}}(\underline{A})$ (for a category $\underline{A}$) is said to satisfy the right Ore condition if for any pair of morphisms $s\in\underline{A}(c,d)\cap S$, and $f\in\underline{A}(b,d)$ there exist $a\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{A},g\in\underline{A}(a,b)$, and $u\in\underline{A}(a,c)$ such that the following diagram commutes: $\begin{CD}a@>{g}>{}>b\\ @V{}V{u}V@V{}V{f}V\\ c@>{s}>{}>d\end{CD}$ The left Ore condition is the categorical dual to the right Ore condition.
Definition 2.3.1. Let $\underline{C}$ be a category with a weight structure $w$ and let $\underline{E}$ be some triangulated category with a functor $F$ from $\underline{C}$ to $\underline{E}$. We will say that $\underline{E}$ admits a weight structure compatible with $w$ if there is a weight structure $w_{\underline{E}}$ on $\underline{E}$ such that $F$ is $w$-exact. If such a weight structure is unique we will say that $w$ induces a weight structure on $\underline{E}$.
Definition 3.1.1. We call a triangle $X_{1}\to X\to X_{2}\to X_{1}[1]$ a weak weight decomposition of $X$ if $X_{1}\in\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and $X_{2}\in\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$. Usually we will consider weak weight decompositions in some triangulated subcategory $\underline{D}$ of $\underline{C}$. This means that $X_{1}$ and $X_{2}$ are objects of $\underline{D}$. Using this definition, the assertion 1 of Proposition 2.3.3 can be reformulated as follows: any element of $\underline{D}$ possesses a weak weight decomposition inside $\underline{D}$.
Definition 3.2.5. Let $F:\underline{C}\to\underline{C}^{\prime}$ be a triangulated functor between triangulated categories which is weight-exact with respect to some weight structures $w$ and $w^{\prime}$ (on $\underline{C}$ and $\underline{C}^{\prime}$, respectively). We say that $F$ satisfies the strong left weight lifting property if for any object $X$ of $\underline{C}$ such that $F(X)\in\underline{C}^{\prime}_{w^{\prime}\geq 0}$ there exists a triangle $T\to X\to X_{\geq 0}\to T[1],$ where $F(T)=0$ and $X_{\geq 0}\in\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$. Using the octahedron axiom and weak weight decompositions of $T$ one can show that the existence of a triangle as above is equivalent to the existence of a distinguished triangle $T^{\prime}\to X\to X^{\prime}_{\geq 0}\to T[1]$ where $T^{\prime}\in(\operatorname{Obj}\underline{D})\cap\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and $X^{\prime}_{\geq 0}\in\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$. We will say that $F$ satisfies strong right weight lifting property if the corresponding functor on the opposite triangulated categories satisfies the strong left weight lifting property.
Definition 4.1.1. Elements of $\bigcap\limits_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\leq n}$ (resp. of $\bigcap\limits_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\geq n}$) are called right degenerate (resp. left degenerate). We will say that $w$ is right non-degenerate (resp. left non-degenerate) if $\bigcap\limits_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\leq n}=\{0\}$ (resp. $\bigcap\limits_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\geq n}=\{0\}$).
Definition 2.2.1. I. A pair of subclasses $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0},\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}\subset\operatorname{Obj}% \underline{C}$ will be said to define a weight structure $w$ for a triangulated category $\underline{C}$ if they satisfy the following conditions. (i) $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0},\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ are Karoubi-closed in $\underline{C}$ (i.e., contain all $\underline{C}$-retracts of their elements). (ii) Semi-invariance with respect to translations. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\subset\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}[1]$, $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]\subset\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$. (iii) Orthogonality. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\perp\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$. (iv) Weight decompositions. For any $M\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ there exists a distinguished triangle $X\to M\to Y{\to}X[1]$ such that $X\in\underline{C}_{w\leq 0},\ Y\in\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$. II. The category ${\underline{Hw}}\subset\underline{C}$ whose objects are $\underline{C}_{w=0}=\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}\cap\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and morphisms are ${\underline{Hw}}(Z,T)=\underline{C}(Z,T)$ for $Z,T\in\underline{C}_{w=0}$, is called the heart of $w$. III. $\underline{C}_{w\geq i}$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{w\leq i}$, resp. $\underline{C}_{w=i}$) will denote $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[i]$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}[i]$, resp. $\underline{C}_{w=0}[i]$). IV. We denote $\underline{C}_{w\geq i}\cap\underline{C}_{w\leq j}$ by $\underline{C}_{[i,j]}$ (so it equals $\{0\}$ for $i>j$). Elements of $\underline{C}_{[i,j]}$ are said to have length at most $j-i$. The length of an object $X\in\underline{C}$ is the minimal $n\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}$ such that $X$ has length less or equal $n$. $\underline{C}^{b}\subset\underline{C}$ will be the category whose object class is $\cup_{i,j\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{[i,j]}$. V. We will say that $(\underline{C},w)$ is bounded if $\underline{C}^{b}=\underline{C}$ (i.e., if $\cup_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\leq i}=\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}% =\cup_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\geq i}$). For any full subcategory $\underline{D}$ of $\underline{C}$ we will use the notation $\underline{D}^{b}$ for the full subcategory of $\underline{C}$ whose objects are $\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}^{b}\cap\operatorname{Obj}\underline{D}$ VI. Let $\underline{C}$ and $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ be triangulated categories endowed with weight structures $w$ and $w^{\prime}$, respectively; let $F:\underline{C}\to\underline{C}^{\prime}$ be an exact functor. $F$ is said to be weight-exact (with respect to $w,w^{\prime}$) if it maps $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ into $\underline{C}^{\prime}_{w^{\prime}\leq 0}$ and maps $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ into $\underline{C}^{\prime}_{w^{\prime}\geq 0}$. VII Let $\underline{D}$ be a full triangulated subcategory of $\underline{C}$. We will say that $w$ restricts to it if the classes $\operatorname{Obj}\underline{D}\cap\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and $\operatorname{Obj}\underline{D}\cap\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ give a weight structure $w_{\underline{D}}$ on $\underline{D}$.
Definition 3.1. We say that a left $R$-module $M$ is $\text{FP}_{n}$-injective if ${\rm Ext}^{1}_{R}(F,M)=0$ for all $F\in\mathcal{FP}_{n}$ (this may include the case $n=\infty$). We denote by $\mathcal{FP}_{n}\text{-}{\rm Inj}$ the class of all $\text{FP}_{n}$-injective modules.
Definition 3.2. We say that a left $R$-module $M$ is $\text{FP}_{n}$-flat if ${\rm Tor}_{1}^{R}(F,M)=0$ for all $F\in\mathcal{FP}_{n}$ (this may include the case $n=\infty$). We denote by $\mathcal{FP}_{n}\text{-}{\rm Flat}$ the class of all $\text{FP}_{n}$-flat modules.
Definition 2.2. A ring $R$ is $n$-coherent if $\mathcal{FP}_{n}\subseteq\mathcal{FP}_{n+1}$.
Definition 4.8. For $n\in\mathbb{N}$, or $n=\infty$, a $C^{n,\mathrm{sym}}$-law between linear sets $U,U^{\prime}$ is family of morphism of $k$-fold groupoids, for $k=0,\ldots,n$, $\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{k}}:\mathsf{Gsy}^{\mathsf{k}}U\to\mathsf{Gsy}^{\mathsf{k}}% U^{\prime}$ which are compatible with each other: with notation from Equation (4.5), we have $\forall k=1,\ldots,n:\qquad\pi_{k}\circ\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{k}}=(\mathbf{f}^{% \mathsf{k-1}}\times\mathrm{id}_{\mathbb{K}})\circ\pi_{k}.$ Such a law is called symmetric if each $\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{k}}$ commutes with the $S_{k}$-action, and it is called homogeneous if it commutes wih scalar actions: $\forall\mathbf{s}\in\mathbb{K}^{n}:\qquad\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{n}}\circ\Phi_{% \mathbf{s}}^{\alpha}=\Phi_{\mathbf{s}}^{\alpha}\circ\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{n}}.$
Definition 3.10. Let $N=\{a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}\}\subset\mathbb{N}$ be a non-empty finite subset. We consider $N$ as ordered, with the natural order inherited from $\mathbb{N}$: we assume that $a_{1}<\ldots<a_{n}$. The $n$-fold groupoid $\mathsf{G}^{N}U$ is defined as in the preceding theorem by $\mathsf{G}^{N}U:=(\mathsf{G}^{\{a_{n}\}}\circ\cdots\circ\mathsf{G}^{\{a_{1}\}}% )U.$ For each vertex $\alpha$, the vertex spaces are denoted by $\mathsf{G}^{\alpha;N}U$; the top vertex set is $\mathsf{G}^{N;N}U=U^{N}=(\ldots(U^{\{a_{1}\}})^{\{a_{2}\}}\ldots)^{\{a_{n}\}}$ and the bottom vertex set is $\mathsf{G}^{\emptyset;N}U=U\times\mathbb{K}^{n}$. For each edge $(\beta,\alpha)$, the edge projections and injections are denoted by $\pi^{\beta,\alpha;N}_{U}$, resp. $z^{\beta,\alpha;N}_{U}$, and the groupoid law belonging to the edge category is denoted by $\ast^{\beta,\alpha;N}$. More generally, if $(\gamma,\alpha)$ is a $k$-cube in ${\mathcal{P}}(N)$ (so $\gamma\subset\alpha$ and $|\alpha\setminus\gamma|=k$), there is a unique section $z^{\gamma,\alpha;N}:\mathsf{G}^{\gamma;N}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\alpha;N}U,$ and there are $2^{k}$ projections $\pi^{\gamma,\alpha;N}_{\bf\sigma}:\mathsf{G}^{\alpha;N}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\gamma;% N}U$ (at each step there is a choice between target and source projection). The section $z^{\emptyset,N;N}$ is called the bottom-up section, and the $2^{n}$ projections $\pi^{\emptyset,N;N}$ are called the top-down projections.
Definition B.5. Let $C=(C_{0},C_{1},\ast)$ be a small $n$-fold cat. Then the opposite cat $C^{opp}$ is again a small $n$-fold cat. Iterating this procedure, for each subset $\gamma\subset\mathsf{n}$ we get the $\gamma$-opposite $n$-fold cat $C^{\gamma{\rm-opp}}$ defined by taking at level $i$ the opposite cat structure if $i\in\gamma$ and the original one else.
Definition E.1. Assume $A\subset V_{1}$, $B\subset V_{2}$, $C\subset W$ are linear sets and $f:A\to C$ and $g:B\to C$ maps. The pullback (in the concrete category of linear sets with set maps), $(A\times_{C}B,A,B,p_{A},p_{B},f,g)$, of these data is the linear set defined by $\displaystyle P:=A\times_{C}B$ $\displaystyle:=\{(a,b)\in A\times B\mid f(a)=g(b)\}\subset V_{1}\times V_{2},$ together with its two projections $p_{A}:P\to A$ and $p_{B}:P\to B$ fitting into the commutative diagram of mappings $\displaystyle\begin{matrix}P&\to&B\cr\downarrow&&\downarrow\cr A&\to&C.\end{matrix}$ In the following, we distinguish the set $P$ and the whole structure of pullback, denoted by $A\times_{C}B$. Note that, if $C=0$ is a point, then $P$ is the usual cartesian product $A\times B$ of sets.
Definition 3.1. For a linear set $U\subset V$, we define sets, zero section, projections $\displaystyle\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}U$ $\displaystyle=U^{\{1\}}=\{(v_{0},v_{1},t_{1})\in V^{2}\times\mathbb{K}\mid\,v_% {0}\in U,v_{0}+v_{1}t_{1}\in U\},$ $\displaystyle\mathsf{G}^{\emptyset;\mathsf{1}}U$ $\displaystyle=U\times\mathbb{K}$ $\displaystyle z^{\emptyset,\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}},:\mathsf{G}^{\emptyset;% \mathsf{1}}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}U,$ $\displaystyle\quad(v_{0},t_{1})\mapsto(v_{0},0,t_{1})$ $\displaystyle\pi^{\emptyset,\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}_{0}:\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1};% \mathsf{1}}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\emptyset;\mathsf{1}}U$ $\displaystyle\quad(v_{0},v_{1},t_{1})\mapsto(v_{0},t_{1}),$ $\displaystyle\pi^{\emptyset,\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}_{1}:\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1};% \mathsf{1}}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\emptyset;\mathsf{1}}U$ $\displaystyle\quad(v_{0},v_{1},t_{1})\mapsto(v_{0}+t_{1}v_{1},t_{1}),$ and composition given on $U^{\mathsf{1}}\times_{U\times\mathbb{K}}U^{\mathsf{1}}$ by by $(v_{0}^{\prime},v_{1}^{\prime},t_{1})\ast(v_{0},v_{1},t)=(v_{0},v_{1}+v_{1}^{% \prime},t).$ These data define a groupoid, denoted by $U^{\{1\}}$ in Part I, $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}U:=(\mathsf{G}^{\emptyset;\mathsf{1}}U,\mathsf{G}^{% \mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}U,\pi^{\emptyset,\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}_{\sigma},z^{% \emptyset,\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}},*).$ For fixed $t_{1}=t$, we use the notation $\mathsf{G}_{t}^{\mathsf{1}}U$ for the groupoid obtained by freezing the last variable. Its morphism set is $\mathsf{G}_{t}^{\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}U=U_{t}=\{(v_{0},v_{1})\in V^{2}\mid\,(v% _{0},v_{1},t)\in U^{\mathsf{1}}\}.$ The description by triples $(v_{0},v_{1},t_{1})$ will be called the affine coordinates of $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}U$.
Definition B.9. Fix some ccat $\underline{\rm C}$. We assume that one can form pullbacks in $\underline{\rm C}$ (cf. Appendix E). A cat-rule $\mathsf{Q}$ on $\underline{\rm C}$ is a pullback-preserving functor from $\underline{\rm C}$ to C-Cat. That is, we have a functor $\mathsf{Q}=\mathsf{Q}^{\mathsf{1}}=\mathsf{Q}^{\{1\}}$ from $\underline{\rm C}$ to itself, such that each set $\mathsf{Q}^{\mathsf{1}}U$ carries a structure of small cat of type $\underline{\rm C}$ (with object set $\mathsf{Q}^{\emptyset;\mathsf{1}}U$, morphism set $\mathsf{Q}^{\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}U$ and composition $\ast_{1}$), and each $\mathsf{Q}f:\mathsf{Q}U\to\mathsf{Q}U^{\prime}$ is a morphism of small cats. Moreover, we require that $\mathsf{Q}$ be compatible with (set-theoretic) pullbacks, i.e., $\mathsf{Q}(A\times_{B}C)=\mathsf{Q}A\times_{\mathsf{Q}B}\mathsf{Q}C.$
Definition 3.17. For $f:U\to U^{\prime}$ as in Theorem 3.15, the unique laws determined by $f$ will be denoted ${\mathsf{Gfi}}^{\mathsf{n}}f:{\mathsf{Gfi}}^{\mathsf{n}}U\to{\mathsf{Gfi}}^{% \mathsf{n}}U^{\prime},\qquad{\mathsf{Gfi}}^{\overline{\mathsf{n}}}f:{\mathsf{% Gfi}}^{\overline{\mathsf{n}}}U\to{\mathsf{Gfi}}^{\overline{\mathsf{n}}}U^{% \prime},$ and if $f$ is a $C^{n}$-map as in Theorem 3.16, the unique induced laws are denoted by $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}f:=\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{n}}:\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}U\to% \mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}U^{\prime},\qquad\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{n}}}f:=% \mathbf{f}^{\overline{\mathsf{n}}}:\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{n}}}U\to% \mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{n}}}U^{\prime}.$ In both situations, we say that these laws are obtained “by deriving the map $f$”. We also use such notation and language when $f$ is polynomial law, and especially when $f$ is constant, linear or bilinear.
Definition C.3. An $n$-fold equivalence relation on $M$ is a subgroupoid of $\mathsf{PG}^{\mathsf{n}}M$.
Definition 4.2 (The ring action). For any $\alpha=\{\alpha_{1},\ldots,\alpha_{\ell}\}\in{\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})$, let $V_{\alpha}$ be a copy of $V$, on which we let act the ring $\mathbb{K}^{n}$ (direct product of rings) in the following way: $\forall\mathbf{t}\in\mathbb{K}^{n},\forall v_{\alpha}\in V_{\alpha}:\quad% \mathbf{t}.v_{\alpha}:=t_{\alpha_{1}}\cdots t_{\alpha_{\ell}}\cdot v_{\alpha}.$
Definition B.1. For $n=1$, a small $1$-fold cat is a small cat, and this defines the concrete category $\underline{\rm Cat}_{1}$ of small cats. A small $n$-fold cat is a small cat $C$ of type $\underline{\rm Cat}_{n-1}$, and a morphism of small $n$-fold cats is a functor $f:C\to C^{\prime}$ which is also a morphism with respect to the $\underline{\rm Cat}_{n-1}$-structures on $C$ and $C^{\prime}$. This defines a concrete category $\underline{\rm Cat}_{n}$. In the same way, the concrete category $\underline{\rm Goid}_{n}$ of $n$-fold groupoids is defined.
Definition 3.6. Let $\mathbb{K}$ be an arbitary ring and $(U,V)$, $(U^{\prime},V^{\prime})$ be linear sets. A law of class $C^{1}$ is a morphism $\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{1}}=(\mathbf{f}^{\emptyset;1},\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{1};% \mathsf{1}})$ from $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}U$ to $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}U^{\prime}$ such that $0_{U^{\prime}}\circ\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{1}}=0_{U}$, and a homogeneous law is a morphism $\mathbf{f}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}$ from $\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U$ to $\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U^{\prime}$ such that $\overline{0}_{U^{\prime}}\circ\mathbf{f}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}=\overline{0}_% {U}$. The concrete category of linear sets with $C^{1}$-laws is given by linear sets $((U,V);(\mathsf{G}^{\emptyset;\mathsf{1}}U,\mathsf{G}^{\emptyset;\mathsf{1}}V)% ;(\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}U,\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}V))$ and morphisms $(f,\mathbf{f}^{\emptyset;1},\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}})$. In this ccat, pullbacks are defined by Definition E.2.
Definition 3.2. For a linear set $U\subset V$, we define vertex sets $\displaystyle\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}};\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U$ $\displaystyle=U^{\overline{\{1\}}}=\{(v_{0},v_{1},s_{1},t_{1})\in V^{2}\times% \mathbb{K}^{2}\mid\,v_{0}\in U,v_{0}+v_{1}s_{1}t_{1}\in U\},$ $\displaystyle\mathsf{G}^{\emptyset;\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U$ $\displaystyle=U\times\mathbb{K},$ $\displaystyle\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1};\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U$ $\displaystyle=\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1};\mathsf{1}}U=U^{\{1\}},$ $\displaystyle\mathsf{G}^{\{1^{\prime}\};\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U$ $\displaystyle=U\times\mathbb{K}^{2},$ and edge projections $\pi^{\beta,\alpha;\overline{\mathsf{1}}}_{\sigma}:\mathsf{G}^{\alpha;\overline% {\mathsf{1}}}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\beta;\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U$ for each of the four edges $(\beta,\alpha)$, as described in Part I, Section 3.2, as well as zero sections and four compositions, as defined in loc. cit. These data define a small double category $\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U$ (and denoted by $U^{\overline{\{1\}}}$ from Part I). Sometimes, as in Part I, projections and composition corresponding to the two edges of second kind will be denoted by $\partial$ and $\bullet$.
Definition 3.13. We denote by $C^{n}_{\mathbb{K}}$-linset (resp. $C^{\overline{n}}_{\mathbb{K}}$-linset) the concrete category of linear sets with (homogeneous) $C^{n}$-laws as morphisms: objects of $C^{n}_{\mathbb{K}}$-linset are families of linear sets $(U,\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}U;V,\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}V)$ and morphisms are $C^{n}$-laws $(f,\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{n}})$. Pullbacks in this category are defined by the base linear set $A\times_{C}B$ (see Definition E.2) and the extended sets $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}(A\times_{C}B):=\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}A\times_{\mathsf% {G}^{\mathsf{n}}C}\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}B$ (which form again an $n$-fold groupoid, by induction from Theorem E.3). In particular, for $C=0$ we get the behaviour of $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}$ with respect to cartesian products $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}(A\times B)=\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}A\times_{\mathsf{G}^% {\mathsf{n}}0}\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}B.$ Similar definitions are given for the ccat of linear sets with homogeneous $C^{n}$-laws, with the symbol $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}$ replaced by $\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{n}}}$.
Definition A.1. A vertex $\alpha$ of the $n+1$-hypercube is called (1) an old vertex if it belongs to ${\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})$, i.e., if $n+1\notin\alpha$, (2) a new vertex if $n+1\in\alpha$. We distinguish three kinds of edges of ${\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n+1})$: an (oriented) edge $(\beta,\alpha)$ is called (1) an old edge if both $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are old vertices; (2) a copy of an old edge if both $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are new vertices (namely, it is a copy of the “old” edge $(\alpha\setminus\{n+1\},\beta\setminus\{n+1\}$)), and (3) a new edge if $\beta$ is an old vertex and $\alpha$ is a new one (so that $\alpha=\beta\cup\{n+1\}$). Similarly, we distinguish three types of faces of ${\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n+1})$: “old” ones, “copies of old” ones, and “new” ones.
Definition B.11. An $n$-fold cat rule on a ccat $\underline{\rm C}$ is given by functors, for each subset $N\subset\mathbb{N}$ of cardinality $n$, $\mathsf{Q}^{N}$, from $\underline{\rm C}$ to the ccat $\underline{\rm C-Cat}_{N}$ of small $n$-fold cats of type ${\rm C}$, and preserving pullbacks.
Definition 4.4. For every vertex $\alpha\in{\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})$ of the natural $n$-hypercube, we define $\mathsf{Gsy}^{\alpha;\mathsf{n}}U:=\{(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\in\prod_{\alpha% \in{\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})}V_{\alpha}\times\mathbb{K}^{n}\mid\,\mathbf{v}\in% \mathsf{Gsy}^{\alpha;\mathsf{n}}_{\mathbf{t}}U\}.$ Note that the bottom vertex, corresponding to $\alpha=\emptyset$, is $\mathsf{Gsy}^{\emptyset;\mathsf{n}}U=U\times\mathbb{K}^{n}.$ Projections, zero sections and composition $\ast$ are defined as in the theorem, and with these structures $\mathsf{Gsy}^{\mathsf{n}}U$ is an edge-symmetric $n$-fold groupoid. It comes together with a family of morphisms $\pi_{n}:\mathsf{Gsy}^{\mathsf{n}}U\rightrightarrows\mathsf{Gsy}^{\mathsf{n-1}}% U\times\mathbb{K}$ and a morphism onto the trivial $n$-fold groupoid $\mathbb{K}^{n}$: $\mathsf{Gsy}^{\mathsf{n}}U\to\mathsf{Gsy}^{\mathsf{n}}0=\mathbb{K}^{n},\quad(% \mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\mapsto\mathbf{t}$ The inverse image of $(\mathbb{K}^{\times})^{n}$ under this morpism is called the finite part of $\mathsf{Gsy}^{\mathsf{n}}U$: $\mathsf{Gsyfi}^{\alpha,\mathsf{n}}U:=\{(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\in\mathsf{Gsy}^% {\alpha,\mathsf{n}}U\mid\forall i:t_{i}\in\mathbb{K}^{\times}\}.$
Definition 2.1 (Full cubic $C^{n}$). Under the assumptions of topological differential calculus (i.e., $\mathbb{K}$ a topological base ring with dense unit group, $V,W$ topological $\mathbb{K}$-modules, $U$ open in $V$; cf. Part I), a map $f:U\to W$ is called of class $C^{n}$ if it is $C^{n-1}$ and if $f^{[n-1]}$ is $C^{1}$; so the map $f^{[n]}:=(f^{[n-1]})^{[1]}$ exists and is continuous on its domain of definition $U^{[n]}=(U^{[n-1]})^{[1]}.$
Definition B.4. Let $\tau\in S_{n}$ be a permutation of $\mathsf{n}$. For a small $n$-fold cat $C=(C_{\alpha})_{\alpha\in{\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})}$, the $\tau$-transposed $n$-fold cat is given by $C^{\tau}:=(C_{\tau(\alpha)})_{\alpha\in{\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})}$. The $n$-fold cat $(C_{\alpha})_{\alpha\in{\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})}$ is called edge-symmetric if, for each $\tau\in S_{n}$, there is an isomorphism of $n$-fold cats $f_{\tau}:C\to C^{\tau}$ such that $f_{\tau}\circ f_{\nu}=f_{\tau\nu}$ and $f_{\mathrm{id}}=\mathrm{id}_{C}$. In other words, we have an action of $S_{n}$ by isomorphisms.2 In work of Brown and Higgins [BH81], and in [BHS11], it is always assumed that $n$-fold cats and groupoids are edge symmetric, and notation is then chosen such that, whenever $\alpha$ and $\alpha^{\prime}$ are conjugate under $S_{n}$ (i.e., have same cardinality), $C_{\alpha}$ and $C_{\alpha^{\prime}}$ are denoted by the same symbols.
Definition 3.4. The finite part of $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}U$, denoted by ${\mathsf{Gfi}}^{\mathsf{1}}U$, is the subgroupoid lying over the invertible scalars $\mathbb{K}^{\times}$, and denoted by $(U^{\{1\}})^{\times}$ in Part I. The finite part of $\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U$, denoted by ${\mathsf{Gfi}}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U$, is the sub-doublecat lying over $\mathbb{K}^{\times}\times\mathbb{K}^{\times}\downdownarrows\mathbb{K}^{\times}$, and denoted by $(\mathbf{U}^{\overline{\{1\}}})^{\times}$ in Theorem 3.6 of Part I. Recall from that theorem that the finite part is isomorphic to the direct product of the pair groupoid of $U$ with the one of $\mathbb{K}^{\times}$.
Definition A.2. Let $\alpha\subset N$, with preceding notation. A vertex of the form $(\alpha,\overline{N})$ is called an $N$-vertex, a vertex of the form $(\alpha^{\prime},\overline{N})$ an $N^{\prime}$-vertex, and a vertex of the form $(\overline{\alpha},\overline{N})$ is called a saturated vertex. A vertex that is of neither of these forms will be called generic.
Definition B.8. A two-typed $2n$-fold cat is a small $2n$-fold cat, together with a fixed structure of small $n$-fold cat of type $\underline{\rm Cat}_{n}$. As index set, we then use the two-typed hypercupe ${\mathcal{P}}(\overline{\mathsf{n}})$, and we often denote projections and composition laws corresponding to edges of the second kind by the symbols $\partial$ and $\bullet$, whereas for those corresponding to edges of the first kind we use $\pi$ and $\ast$.
Definition 2.2 (Symmetric $C^{n,\mathrm{sym}}$). Under assumptions as above, for fixed $t\in\mathbb{K}$, let $U_{t}:=\{(v_{0},v_{1})\in V^{2}\mid\,v_{0}\in U,v_{0}+tv_{1}\in U\}$ and write, for a $C^{1}$-map $f:U\to W$, $f_{t}^{[1]}:U_{t}\to W,\quad(v_{0},v_{1})\mapsto f^{[1]}(v_{0},v_{1},t).$ By induction, for fixed $\mathbf{t}=(t_{1},\ldots,t_{n})\in\mathbb{K}^{n}$, we put, whenever defined, $f_{\mathbf{t}}^{[n]}:=f_{t_{1},\ldots,t_{n}}^{[n]}:=(f_{t_{1},\ldots,t_{n-1}}^% {[n-1]})_{t_{n}}^{[1]}:U_{\mathbf{t}}^{[n]}:=(\ldots(U_{t_{1}})_{t_{2}}\ldots)% _{t_{n}}\to W,$ and we say that $f$ is $C^{n,\mathrm{sym}}$ if it is $C^{n-1,\mathrm{sym}}$, and if the map $f^{[n-1]}_{(t_{1},\ldots,t_{n-1})}$ is $C^{1}$ (so that, in particular, $f^{[n]}_{\mathbf{t}}$ is defined and continuous).
Definition 3.3. By terminal object we mean the linear set $0=(0,0)$ (zero $\mathbb{K}$-module). Recall from Part I that $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}0=(\mathbb{K},\mathbb{K})$ has a trivial groupoid structure, and that the double cat $\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}0$ reduces to the left action category $(\mathbb{K},\mathbb{K}^{2})$ of $\mathbb{K}$; recall also that there are canonical morphisms of groupoids $0_{U}:\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}0,\qquad\overline{0}_{% U}:\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}0.$
Definition 5.1. With $N$ and $\alpha\in{\mathcal{P}}(N)$ as above, for all $j\in N$, we define $\langle\alpha,j\rangle:=\Bigr{\{}\begin{matrix}\{j\}&\mbox{ if }&j\in\alpha\cr% \emptyset&\mbox{ if }&j\notin\alpha.\end{matrix}$
Definition 3.12. Assume $(U,V)$, $(U^{\prime},V^{\prime})$ are linear sets over $\mathbb{K}$. A $C^{n}$-law between $U$ and $U^{\prime}$ is given by morphisms of $k$-fold groupoids $\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{k}}:\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{k}}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{k}}U^{\prime}$ for $k=0,\ldots,n$, compatible with each other, in the sense that they complete diagram (3.4) $\begin{matrix}\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{k}}U=\mathsf{G}^{\{k\}}(\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{% k-1}}U)&\buildrel{\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{k}}}\over{\to}&\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{k}}U^% {\prime}\cr\pi^{n}_{\sigma}\downdownarrows\quad\uparrow z^{n}&&\downdownarrows% \quad\uparrow\cr\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{k-1}}U\times\mathbb{K}_{k}&\buildrel{% \mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{k-1}}\times\mathrm{id}_{\mathbb{K}}}\over{\to}&\mathsf{G}^% {\mathsf{k-1}}U^{\prime}\times\mathbb{K}_{k}.\end{matrix}$ The set map $f:=\mathbf{f}^{\emptyset}:U\to U^{\prime}$ is called the base map of $\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{n}}$. A $C^{\infty}$-law between $U$ and $U^{\prime}$ is given by morphisms of $k$-fold groupoids $\mathbf{f}^{\mathsf{k}}:\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{k}}U\to\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{k}}U^{\prime}$ for each $k\in\mathbb{N}$ which are compatible with each other, in the sense explained above. In the same way, homogeneous laws are defined by replacing $\mathsf{n}$ by $\overline{\mathsf{n}}$ and morphisms of $n$-fold groupoids by morphisms of $2n$-fold categories.
Definition B.6. In a small $n$-fold cat, the $n$-fold source map is defined by $\xi:=\pi^{\emptyset,\mathsf{1}}_{0}\circ\pi^{\mathsf{1},\mathsf{2}}_{0}\ldots% \circ\pi^{\mathsf{n-1},\mathsf{n}}_{0}:C_{\mathsf{n}}\to C_{\emptyset}.$ More generally, for any subset $\gamma\subset\mathsf{n}$, we define the $\gamma$-top-down projection $\xi_{\gamma}:=\pi^{\emptyset,\mathsf{1}}_{k_{1}}\circ\pi^{\mathsf{1},\mathsf{2% }}_{k_{2}}\ldots\circ\pi^{\mathsf{n-1},\mathsf{n}}_{k_{n}}:C_{\mathsf{n}}\to C% _{\emptyset}$ where $k_{i}=1$ (target) if $i\in\gamma$ and $k_{i}=0$ (source) if $i\notin\gamma$. In other words, this is the $n$-fold source map of $C^{\gamma{\rm-opp}}$.
Definition 3.18. By scaledoid, we mean the family of $n$-fold groupoids, resp. of $2n$-fold categories $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{n}}0,\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{n}}}0$, for $n\in\mathbb{N}$, where $0=(\{0\},\{0\})$ is the zero-space, seen as linear set over $\mathbb{K}$.
Definition E.2. Recall from Definition 3.6 the ccat of linear sets with $C^{1}$-laws. With notation as above, we define the pullback in the concrete cat of linear sets with $C^{1}$-laws to be the set-theoretic pullback of $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}A$ and $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}C$ via $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}f$ and $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}g$, i.e., it is given by the base set $A\times_{C}B$ and the extended sets $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}(A\times_{C}B):=\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}A\times_{\mathsf% {G}^{\mathsf{1}}C}\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}B.$ Similar definitions are given for $\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}$ and $\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\{k\}}}$. In particular, with $\mathbb{K}_{1}:=0^{\{1\}}$, $\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}(A\times B)=\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}A\times_{\mathbb{K}_% {1}}\mathsf{G}^{\mathsf{1}}B,\qquad\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}(A\times B% )=\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}A\times_{\mathbb{K}_{1}\times\mathbb{K}_{1% }}\mathsf{G}^{\overline{\mathsf{1}}}B.$
Definition A.3. An edge $(\beta,\alpha)\in{\mathcal{P}}(\overline{N})$ will be called of first kind if the unique element of $\alpha\setminus\beta$ belongs to $N$, and of second kind if it belongs to $N^{\prime}$. We distinguish three kinds of faces, namely faces such that (a) all of its edges are of first kind, (b) all of its edges are of second kind, (c) it has two edges of the first and two of the second kind.
Definition 2.8. We call the number $d_{+}(X^{*})$ the symmetric $p$-adic dimension of $X$, denoted ${\rm Dim}_{+}(X)$, and call the number $d_{-}(X^{*})$ the exterior $p$-adic dimension of $X$, denoted ${\rm Dim}_{-}(X)$.
Definition 2.1 An automorphism $\xi\in\mathrm{Aut}(\mathrm{End}(F(X)))$ which acts identically on ${\mathrm{Aut}}_{l}(F(X))$, is called a linearly stable automorphism of $\mathrm{End}(F(X))$.
